Service accounts, pod identity.

Let us look at what the kube-let actually mounts. When a pod is scheduled, the kube-let asks the ay-pee-eye server's token request ay-pee-eye for a token for the pod's service account, and it mounts three files into the pod at a well known path. The certificate authority file, for verifying tee-el-ess. The namespace, as a plain string. And the token itself, a json web token signed by the cluster's signing key.

In cluster clients, like the official libraries or kubectl running inside a pod, read those three files to build an authenticated connection. They do not need any configuration. The identity is just there, mounted into the pod.

The tokens projected today are modern, bound tokens. They expire, typically after an hour, and the kube-let rotates them automatically. They carry an audience, so a token is only valid for the ay-pee-eye server, not for some other service. And they are bound to the pod, so when the pod is deleted, the token is revoked. The old style, long lived tokens, a never expiring secret per account, have been phased out. Treat any such long lived token secret as suspicious.

And one best practice. By default the kube-let mounts a token into every pod, even pods that never call the ay-pee-eye server. For those, set automount service account token to false, and mount nothing at all. A pure web server that never talks to kubernetes has no reason to carry a credential it could leak. Mount the token only where the workload genuinely needs it.
